{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504060"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:09:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2295"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2295"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.18,0,0.73,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31308"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2295"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17134"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1654"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"573"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1161"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31308"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents with a two day history of increasing difficulty with walking. He tends to misstep and stumble when walking around his garden. He has no bowel or bladder symptoms. Over the last three weeks he has had persistent back pain. This is on a background of prostate cancer. On physical examination he has an obvious ataxia. There has tenderness over his lower thoracic spine and impaired proprioception in his lower limbs on neurological examination. A digital rectal examination is performed, which revealed a hard, craggy prostate and normal anal tone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigation is most likely to reveal the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-ray of the whole spine","CT of the whole spine","Lumbar puncture","MRI of the whole spine","CT head and neck"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has signs and symptoms consistent with spinal cord compression. The most sensitive and specific investigation of choice is an \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the whole spine\u003C/strong\u003E. MRI is the modality of choice because it not only reveals the degree of metastatic involvement of the vertebrae but also clearly images the spinal canal/cord and depending on the degree of signal change seen in the cord. It also allows an assessment of the severity of the actual cord compression which might correlate with the examination findings.\u0026nbsp;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT spine\u003C/strong\u003E can detect cord compression but it would be poorly imaged as compared to MRI spine. An \u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray of the whole spine\u003C/strong\u003E does not image the cord so cord compression/involvement and its severity cannot be assessed and it is also not very sensitive in picking up all bony lesions which should not be miss as they may be treatable/managed with therapies early e.g. radiotherapy for symptomatic control. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT head and neck\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect cerebral metastases, although prostate cancers rarely spread to the brain. This history and examination suggest a spinal cord compression rather than a head and neck pathology. This should be part of a working diagnosis, but not first-line in revealing the diagnosis. \u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An MRI of the spine is the preferred investigation for suspected spinal cord compression."],"references":["Carmody RF, Yang PJ, Seeley GW, et al. Spinal cord compression due to metastatic disease: diagnosis with MR imaging versus myelography. Radiology 1989; 173:225.","Li KC, Poon PY. Sensitivity and specificity of MRI in detecting malignant spinal cord compression and in distinguishing malignant from benign compression fractures of vertebrae. Magn Reson Imaging 1988; 6:547."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17134"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2295"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17134"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-05T10:15:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-01-05T10:15:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2295"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu